metadata.name: thébaïde #91
metadata.description:
“Thébaïde” is a french word for wild place, remote and peaceful, where to live in a calm retreat. It's also simply a desert and a synonym of solitude. It comes from Thebaid, an arid region of ancient Egypt and Thebes was the capital.

“thébaïde” is my debut on fx(hash), almost one year since my first works minted on Objkt (a series of Indian ink drawings, in January 2022). After learning the basics of creative coding recently, and a few works with this technique, I decided to create a first generative project. With "thébaïde" I chose to express the minimalist and narrative aspects of my artistic approach (though the title and concept emerged at the end). Gradually the work was resonating with philosophical matters I'm obsessed with since years: time, emptiness, human condition, erosion, desire, chance, combining them into a visual metaphor. The view of a vast area, a changing silhouette, an impenetrable monolith or an opening to elsewhere or nothing, day and night and day and night and dawn and dusk — few elements able to compose a meditative and lasting tableau of questions and feelings.

Press “s” in live mode to save the work.
Made with p5js | 2023
Png | 2000 px x 2000 px | 72 ppi

www.antoniowerli.com

metadata.name: Tangentum #47
metadata.description:
We live in a multiverse: an infinite-dimensional space of variants. Everything exists here. Everything is possible. Each subset of a multiverse has its own unique laws of physics, a set of rules, and its own distinct features.

Tangentum creates a projection of a random multiverse subset to a 2-dimensional plane. Each variation is a unique representation of the force field, that exists somewhere at some point in time.

This work starts a series of my visual exploration of functions, continuity, and boundedness, and I would love to share it with you.


Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience.

Tested with Chrome 107, Safari, and Firefox. Chrome is recommended, other browsers are slower on this artwork.

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.


Made with love and p5js


Controls in fullscreen:
[1] - save PNG 2700 x 1800
[2] - save PNG 5400 x 3800
[3] - save PNG 10800 x 7600
[4] - save PNG 16200 x 11400

metadata.name: Zusammen #106
metadata.description:
The flow of colors across an infinitely maleable grid. Zusammen is built using a framebuffer setup in p5js sampling a rendered direction field to determine the pixel "push" direction, speed, and offsets.

You can run this in fullscreen as instructed below. Doing so will render at the browser's width and height, which will look quite different from the preview version, but will still use the same colors and rules as your token. This can be useful for making wallpapers etc.

You can also continue to run the simulation after it has stopped by hitting the spacebar. This will allow you to further explore the infinite generative space of the piece.

Made with p5js.

Double click to download
Add &highres=true to the URL to get a higher resolution output
Add &fullscreen=true to render to the browser size. N.B. outputs will be somewhat different than the regular view

license information in license.md

metadata.name: Commune #22
metadata.description:
A minimalist composition with a nod towards architecture.

2932 bytes of Vanilla JS.

For more info, see article linked below: Me, Commune, Etc.

In live mode:
’S’ : save as svg (without grain)
‘P’ : save as png (3780x2673)

URL params in live mode:

metadata.name: Hidden Intersections #428
metadata.description:
In this piece, two grids overlap:

1. a perfect one composed of lines drawn on the screen
2. an irregular one composed of linear zones that reference other parts of the screen

Everything you see in the final composition is a result of the overlapping intersections of these two grids with each other, and eventually themselves.


------------

Created as part of #genuaryTogether for #genuary2023, for the 4th day, theme: "intersections".

source code: https://github.com/protozoo/genuary23_04_intersections

controls:
- "s" key: save a png of the display
- "w" key: generate and save a 4k widescreen version of your seed (it will look different, but always be the same)

metadata.name: Southern Gothic #209
metadata.description:
“Southern Gothic” is my debut release on the fxhash platform. The project is created entirely through code. All copyrights are released to the holder of each image output, even for commercial purposes.

“Southern Gothic” borrows its name from the literary genre made famous by writers like Flannery O’Connor and Carson McCullers. Rather than illustrating a singular setting, the code generates an entire rural townscape, thereby, blurring the boundaries between representation and narrative. The individual scenes are framed frontally with an intentionally flat aesthetic character, referencing traditional folk art of the American South. The absence of human figures within these scenes adds to their overwhelming sense of darkness and forlorn. Observing multiple scenes side-by-side, one may even get the strange feeling that something terrible has happened (or is about to happen) in this rural landscape.

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: Clouds over the Mountains #10
metadata.description:
“I'd go as far as the end of a stream or fountain, 
And sit and gaze on cloud rising over the mountain.” 
— Wang Wei (Tang dynasty)

「行到水窮處，坐看雲起時。」
—— 唐·王維

This artwork is inspired by the poem above, and creates a view to “gaze on cloud rising over the mountain”. 
This is also a tribute to the traditional Chinese landscape painting.
